Yes — the **90 × 10^6** is real in that tapered-roller-bearing section, but it is **not** because tapered rollers magically have a different fundamental “L10” definition than ball bearings.

What is happening is this:

For the tapered roller bearings in Shigley pages **583–596**, the book is following the **Timken catalog rating basis** shown in **Fig. 11–15**. That table is labeled:

**“rating at 500 rpm for 3000 hours L10”**

And that is exactly:

[
500 ,\text{rev/min} \times 60 ,\text{min/h} \times 3000 ,\text{h}
= 90{,}000{,}000 ,\text{rev}
= 90 \times 10^6 ,\text{rev}
]

So the mysterious **90 factor** comes from:

* **500 rpm**
* **3000 hours**
* catalog life basis = **90 million revolutions**

Not from some hidden magic formula.

## What tripped you

You are used to ball bearings being referenced to:

[
L_{10} = 10^6 \text{ rev}
]

That is the classic basic rating life basis.

But in this tapered-roller-bearing section, Shigley is not normalizing life to **1 million rev**. He is normalizing to the **catalog rating life used for those Timken tapered bearings**, which is **90 million rev**.

So in **Example 11-8** and **Example 11-11**, when Shigley computes the dimensionless life factor (x_D), he uses:

[
x_D = \frac{L_D}{L_R}
]

with

[
L_R = 90 \times 10^6 \text{ rev}
]

because that is the rating-life basis of the catalog table he is using.

