## So is this “90” a reliability thing?

No. That is the easy confusion.

There are **two different 90s** floating around:

* **(L_{10})** means **90% reliability**
* **(90\times10^6)** rev is the **catalog reference life basis**

Those are not the same thing.

In this section, Shigley is still working with **90% reliability life terminology**, but the **catalog load ratings for these Timken tapered bearings are tabulated at a reference life of 3000 h at 500 rpm**, which equals **90 million rev**.

That is why the life multiple is based on 90 million rev.

## Why Shigley feels confusing here

Because the book does **not stop and loudly say**:

> “Warning: for these tapered Timken tables, the catalog rating basis is 90 million revolutions instead of the usual 1 million.”

Instead, it sort of expects you to notice the header in **Fig. 11–15** and then accept the later formulas.

So your confusion is justified.

## The clean interpretation

For this part of Shigley:

* **Ball-bearing style thinking:**
  normalize life to **(10^6)** rev

* **These Timken tapered-bearing examples:**
  normalize life to the **catalog rating life**, which for Fig. 11–15 is
  **(500 \times 60 \times 3000 = 90\times10^6)** rev

So the **90 factor is a catalog-reference-life conversion**, not a new universal law of tapered bearings.

